track_notes:
This is a well-use route, however please note that it is a scramble involving an exposed traverse requiring use of a chain for protection. The route is not always clear, especially in cloud and the terrain is unforgiving. In winter time the route traverses north-facing snow slopes and requires knowledge of avalanche conditions and skill with an ice-axe to arrest slips and falls. The south-east face of Yamnuska is a major rock-climbing area.
The descent route is described separately as most people continue the traverse to descend the west ridge. This is shorter and uses a long and easy scree-run.
From the summit 2m access into Calgary is good, and there is Bell Canada cell-phone coverage.

Once you have activated Yamnuska, most people descend the west ridge. This route is shorter, has more straight-forward route finding, and includes a marvellous scree-run.
Please note I forgot to turn on my gps for the first couple of hundred metres of the descent.
From the summit the trail is simply the scuffed gravel and scree leading west and down, to the col at the west-end of the mountain. Continue following the trail round to climbers left under the cliff of the SE face of Yamnuska. The path takes you to the scree-run. Descend to the lowest point where the clear trail through the trees takes you back to the car-park.

The trail to the summit of Mt. Yamnuska was reopened with upgrades in November 2021.  The upgrades include some slight route changes, improved trail marking and excellent signage.  The new trail markers make it almost impossible to get off track.  The new signage includes risk assessment points with descriptions of what risks lay ahead.  This allows a hiker to determine whether to continue or to retreat at a couple critical locations. Mt. Yamnuska has been graded as SC6, YDS-3 in the past but there are safety chains to grab that are permanently installed in the most exposed traverse which probably takes the grade to a SC5.  The route here is a loop, with the descent to the scree slope which makes for the easiest descent.  This is a popular mountain for both climbing, scrambling and hiking and there are many areas where activities above could dislodge rocks so wearing a helmet during busy times is prudent.
